          "explanation": "Let\u202fA,\u202fB,\u202fC\u202fdenote whether each person is a knight (true) or a knave (false).\n\n- Alice says \u201cBob is a knave.\u201d This statement is true exactly when\u202fB\u202fis false.\n  - If Alice is a knight (A\u202f=\u202ftrue) the statement must be true \u2192\u202fB\u202f=\u202ffalse.\n  - If Alice is a knave (A\u202f=\u202ffalse) the statement must be false \u2192\u202fB\u202f=\u202ftrue.\n  Hence\u202fB\u202f=\u202f\u00acA.\n\n- Charlie says \u201cAlice is a knave.\u201d This statement is true exactly when\u202fA\u202fis false.\n  - If Charlie is a knight (C\u202f=\u202ftrue) the statement must be true \u2192\u202fA\u202f=\u202ffalse.\n  - If Charlie is a knave (C\u202f=\u202ffalse) the statement must be false \u2192\u202fA\u202f=\u202ftrue.\n  Hence\u202fA\u202f=\u202f\u00acC, which also gives\u202fC\u202f=\u202f\u00acA.\n\nFrom the two relations we have\u202fB\u202f=\u202f\u00acA\u202fand\u202fC\u202f=\u202f\u00acA, so\u202fB\u202f=\u202fC.\n\n- Bob says \u201cAlice and Charlie are of the same type,\u201d i.e.\u202fA\u202f=\u202fC.\n  - Since we already have\u202fA\u202f=\u202f\u00acC, the equality\u202fA\u202f=\u202fC\u202fis never true.\n  - Therefore Bob\u2019s statement must be false, which means Bob is a knave (B\u202f=\u202ffalse).\n\nWith\u202fB\u202f=\u202ffalse, the relation\u202fB\u202f=\u202f\u00acA\u202fgives\u202fA\u202f=\u202ftrue (Alice is a knight).  \nThen\u202fC\u202f=\u202f\u00acA\u202fgives\u202fC\u202f=\u202ffalse (Charlie is a knave).\n\nAll three statements are satisfied:\n- Alice (knight) correctly says Bob is a knave.\n- Bob (knave) falsely claims Alice and Charlie are the same.\n- Charlie (knave) falsely claims Alice is a knave.\n\nThus the only consistent assignment is Alice\u202f=\u202fknight, Bob\u202f=\u202fknave, Charlie\u202f=\u202fknave."
